Name: Manjot Kaur
Content:
Falsy and Truthy Values

JavaScript uses type coercion when evaluating values in boolean contexts (such as in if statements). 

Values that are considered falsy include false, 0, "" (empty string), null, undefined, and NaN.

All other values are truthy.

Name: Manjot Kaur
Content:
Truthy and Falsy Coercion

In some cases, you can use type coercion to achieve desired behaviors.

For example, using !! (double negation) can convert a value to its truthy or falsy equivalent.
